{{Ill|Kamo no Okimi|ja|鴨王 (上古)}} ([[Okimi]] of the [[Kamo clan]]) was the son of [[Kotoshironushi]] and [[Tamakushi-hime]], and brother of [[Himetataraisuzu-hime]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Kamo no Ōkimi • . A History . . of Japan . 日本歴史 |url=https://historyofjapan.co.uk/wiki/kamo-no-okimi/ |access-date=2023-03-20 |website=. A History . . of Japan . 日本歴史 |language=en-GB}}</ref> He was an ancestor of the [[Kamo clan]], and by extension through {{Nihongo|{{ill|Ōtataneko|ja|大田田根子命}}|太田田根子}} the [[Miwa clan]].

He was the father of Empress {{Ill|Nunasokonakatsu-hime|ja|渟名底仲媛}}<ref name=":9">Anston, p. 143 (Vol. 1)</ref>, and thus the father in law of [[Emperor Annei]]<ref name="Brown 251">{{cite book |author=[[Delmer Brown|Brown, Delmer M.]] and Ichirō Ishida |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=w4f5FrmIJKIC&q=Katsuragi |title=A Translation and Study of the Gukanshō, an Interpretative History of Japan Written in 1219 |publisher=University of California Press |year=1979 |isbn=9780520034600 |page=251}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |author=[[Isaac Titsingh|Titsingh, Isaac.]] |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=18oNAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA4 |title=Nihon Ōdai Ichiran |publisher=Royal Asiatic Society, Oriental Translation Fund of Great Britain and Ireland |year=1834 |page=4 |language=fr}}</ref> and the grandfather of [[Emperor Itoku]].<ref name="Varley 892">{{cite book |author=[[H. Paul Varley|Varley, H. Paul.]] |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tVv6OAAACAAJ |title=Jinnō Shōtōki: A Chronicle of Gods and Sovereigns |publisher=Columbia University Press |year=1980 |isbn=9780231049405 |page=89}}</ref>




